Least Safe Counties to Live in California

Ritika Sabharwal

INTRODUCTION

In the past few years, California has experienced brutal wildfires that have destroyed numerous homes and led to poor air quality. Global warming has led to an increase in temperatures, drought conditions, and dry vegetation. This leads to dryness that causes fires in hills and spreads quite far. In the past, these wildfires have destroyed forest ecosystems, homes, and created public health crises. Having lived in California, I have witnessed orange skies due to ashes in the air. Even before COVID, people would wear masks to school due to the polluted air. As a diverse state, there is also a lot of crime in California. Riots, protests, robbery, and shootings are quite common. When buying a house in California, one must consider the crime rate of the area and how prone it is to wildfires. In this tutorial, we will examine trends of wildfire and crime rates in all counties in California, and attempt to discover the least safe counties to live in California to avoid troubles for people in the future.

DATA COLLECTION

Our first phase of the process to analyse the occurences of wildfires in California is to gather data contaning detailed information about wildfires. We are going to use a dataset from https://www.fire.ca.gov/ containing data about wildfires in California from 2013-2020.

We will begin by scraping this data. Since this dataset is from Kaggle, I uploaded the zipfile to a public Git repository, which can be accessed through https://github.com/ritika621/wildfires_data/tree/1bf8cebfd5e7c2775c00fb71e5f76c7fdbbbc102.

Now, we can read the csv into pandas and create a pandas dataframe from the data.

Now that we have collected data about wildfires, we will collect data about crime in California in the same way. We will be scraping data from the Crimes and Clearances dataset reported as part of the Federal Bureau of Investigation's, Uniform Crime Reporting Program. The dataset includes statistcal data about offenses, including criminal homicide, rape, robbery, aggravated assault, burglary, larceny-theft, motor vehicle theft, and arson. This dataset contains data from 1985 - 2020. This can be accessed https://github.com/ritika621/datasets/blob/main/Crimes_and_Clearances_with_Arson-1985-2020%20(2).csv.

Now that we have finished collecting the necessary data annd storing them in pandas dataframes, we will move on to the next process of the data science lifecycle.

DATA MANAGEMENT

In the data management process of the lifecycle, we are going to clean the data so that we can use it for our specific purpose. Data can be messy when we first collect it, and therefore it is important to manipulate data so that it is more organized and easier to analyze. This process is also known as tidying data or data wrangling.

For the wildfires dataset, we are only interested in data from the columns Name, ArchiveYear, AcresBurned, Counties, MajorIncident, Latitude, and Longitude. Since that leaves 33 columns to drop from the dataframe, it will be easier to reassign wildfire_df to be the dataframe with just these columns. In addition, we will drop all missing values from the dataset and reindex the dataset, as we cannot work with empty values for our analysis.

wildfire_df.index = range(len(wildfire_df)) #RE-INDEX THE DF

As we can see, Los Angeles county has the highest numbers for all the crimes. This suggests that Los Angeles county is most prone to crimes. In addiiton, Sacramento county and San Diego County also appear several times.

Now, we will combine wildfires and crimes, to see the top counties most prone to both of these. We will use a scatter plot and a linear regression to see analyse the results.

In [246]:
columns_list = ['Violent_sum', 'Homicide_sum', 'ForRape_sum', 'Robbery_sum', 'AggAssault_sum', 'Property_sum', 'Burglary_sum', 'VehicleTheft_sum', 'LTtotal_sum']
total_crimes_df = crimes_df
total_crimes_df['all_crimes'] = total_crimes_df[columns_list].sum(axis=1)
total_crimes_df = total_crimes_df.drop(columns = ['Robbery_sum','Homicide_sum', 'ForRape_sum', 'Violent_sum', 'AggAssault_sum', 'Property_sum', 'Burglary_sum', 'VehicleTheft_sum', 'LTtotal_sum'])
In [247]:
total_crimes_df.columns = ['Counties', 'All_Crimes']
total_crimes = total_crimes_df["Counties"].str.replace(" County","").to_numpy()
fires_df = wildfire_df.groupby(['Counties'], as_index=False)['AcresBurned'].sum()
total_crimes_df['Counties'] = total_crimes
joint_df = pd.merge(total_crimes_df, fires_df, on = ['Counties'])

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.figure(figsize = (22, 15))
plt.scatter(joint_df['All_Crimes'], joint_df['AcresBurned'])

annotations = joint_df['Counties'].to_numpy()
x = joint_df['All_Crimes'].to_numpy()
y = joint_df['AcresBurned'].to_numpy()
m, b = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)

plt.plot(x, m*x + b)

for i, label in enumerate(annotations):
    plt.annotate(label, (x[i], y[i]))

From this scatterplot, we can see that Los Angeles is the county in California that has had the most number of crimes and most number of acres burned. San Diego and Orange County are the next counties after LA, but with far less statistics than Los Angeles.

HYPOTHESIS TESTING

In this stage of the lifecycle, we make predictions to see if the claims we make can be seen in the future as well through machine learning techniques.

INSIGHTS GAINED

From all the testing and visuals, we can see that Los Angeles County is the least safe county to live in California. With a high number of crimes and widespread wildfires, someone looking to buy a house in California must consider these results. Although Los Angeles is at the hub of Hollywood and has several great attraction, maybe it is only for tourists and not the safest place to settle.
